import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

# URL of the ticketing website
url = 'https://example-ticketing-website.com/events'

# Send a request to fetch the HTML content of the page
response = requests.get(url)
html_content = response.content

# Parse HTML using BeautifulSoup
soup = BeautifulSoup(html_content, 'html.parser')

# Extract ticket prices and availability
tickets = []
for event in soup.find_all('div', class_='event'):
    event_name = event.find('h2', class_='event-name').text.strip()
    price = event.find('span', class_='ticket-price').text.strip()
    availability = event.find('span', class_='ticket-availability').text.strip()
    tickets.append({
        'event_name': event_name,
        'price': price,
        'availability': availability
    })

# Display extracted tickets
for ticket in tickets:
    print(f"Event: {ticket['event_name']}, Price: {ticket['price']}, Availability: {ticket['availability']}")

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

# URL of the fan site with merchandise info
url = 'https://www.examplefansite.com/merchandise'

# Send a GET request to the website
response = requests.get(url)

# Parse the HTML content of the page
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')

# Find the merchandise items container (assuming the items are within a div with class 'merch-item')
merchandise_items = soup.find_all('div', class_='merch-item')

# List to hold merchandise data
merchandise_data = []

# Loop through each merchandise item and extract the relevant info
for item in merchandise_items:
    name = item.find('h2', class_='merch-name').text.strip()
    price = item.find('span', class_='merch-price').text.strip()
    description = item.find('p', class_='merch-description').text.strip()
    merchandise_data.append({
        'name': name,
        'price': price,
        'description': description
    })

# Example: Print the merchandise data
for merch in merchandise_data:
    print(f"Name: {merch['name']}")
    print(f"Price: {merch['price']}")
    print(f"Description: {merch['description']}")
    print('----')

```python
import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

# URL of the website containing podcast episode lists
url = 'http://example.com/podcast'

# Send a GET request to the website
response = requests.get(url)

# Parse the HTML content using BeautifulSoup
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')

# Find the container that holds the podcast episodes
# Update the selector to match the structure of the target website
episode_container = soup.find('div', class_='episode-list')

# Extract individual episodes from the container
episodes = episode_container.find_all('div', class_='episode')

# Iterate through the episodes and collect details
episode_list = []
for episode in episodes:
    title = episode.find('h2', class_='episode-title').text.strip()
    date = episode.find('span', class_='episode-date').text.strip()
    description = episode.find('p', class_='episode-description').text.strip()
    episode_list.append({
        'title': title,
        'date': date,
        'description': description
    })

# Print the collected episode details
for ep in episode_list:
    print(f"Title: {ep['title']}")
    print(f"Date: {ep['date']}")
    print(f"Description: {ep['description']}\n")
```

```python
# Function to parse contact information from a webpage footer
def parse_footer_contact_info(url):
    response = requests.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')
    
    contact_info = {}
    
    # Searching for footer element
    footer = soup.find('footer')
    
    if footer:
        # Extracting email addresses
        contact_info['emails'] = [a['href'].replace('mailto:', '') for a in footer.find_all('a', href=True) if 'mailto:' in a['href']]
        
        # Extracting phone numbers (simple pattern matching for common phone number formats)
        contact_info['phones'] = footer.find_all(text=lambda text: text and re.search(r'\b\d{3}[-.\s]??\d{3}[-.\s]??\d{4}\b', text))
    
    return contact_info
```

import requests

```python
def get_song_lyrics(url):
    # Send an HTTP GET request to the specified URL and handle the response.
    response = requests.get(url)
    if response.status_code != 200:
        return "Failed to retrieve the webpage."
    
    # Parse the HTML content of the response with BeautifulSoup.
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')
    
    # Try to find the lyrics in a specific div with class 'lyrics'.
    lyrics_div = soup.find('div', {'class': 'lyrics'})
    if lyrics_div:
        return lyrics_div.get_text(strip=True)
    
    # If the lyrics are not found in a div with class 'lyrics', gather all paragraphs that have 'lyrics' in their class attributes.
    lyrics_paragraphs = soup.find_all('p')
    lyrics = []
    for para in lyrics_paragraphs:
        if 'class' in para.attrs and 'lyrics' in para['class']:
            lyrics.append(para.get_text(strip=True))
    
    # Combine all gathered lyrics paragraphs into a single string, separated by newlines.
    return "\n".join(lyrics)
```

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

```python
URL = 'https://example-language-learning-site.com'
response = requests.get(URL)
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')

translations = []
items = soup.find_all('div', class_='translation-item')

for item in items:
    source_lang = item.find('span', class_='source-lang').text
    target_lang = item.find('span', class_='target-lang').text
    translations.append({'source': source_lang, 'target': target_lang})

for translation in translations:
    print(f"{translation['source']} -> {translation['target']}")
```

from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
```python
import requests
```

```python
# Request the content of the art gallery webpage
url = 'http://example.com/art-gallery'
response = requests.get(url)
html_content = response.content

# Parse the HTML content using BeautifulSoup
soup = BeautifulSoup(html_content, 'html.parser')

# Find and iterate over each artwork entry
artwork_details = []
for artwork in soup.find_all('div', class_='artwork-entry'):
    title = artwork.find('h2', class_='title').get_text(strip=True)
    artist = artwork.find('span', class_='artist').get_text(strip=True)
    year = artwork.find('span', class_='year').get_text(strip=True)
    description = artwork.find('p', class_='description').get_text(strip=True)
    
    # Optionally, add more details as necessary

    artwork_details.append({
        'title': title,
        'artist': artist,
        'year': year,
        'description': description
    })

# Output the parsed artwork details
for detail in artwork_details:
    print(detail)
```
